---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Jordan Iverson — Iverson Architecture | Heat & Glo Architects" description="Jordan Iverson of Iverson Architecture specifies Heat & Glo Primo II across modern residential and multifamily projects where the fireplace functions as shared infrastructure and spatial organizer." noIndex={true}>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section style="position:relative; min-height:520px; display:flex; align-items:flex-end; overflow:hidden;">
    <img
      src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/937081fe-73df-4957-a0ec-8c5a1bfa3a05/HNG-Primo-II_60-2_2"
      alt="Open contemporary layout with angled stairs and L-shaped low-profile seating around a linear fireplace wall with TV overhead"
      style="position:absolute; inset:0; width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover; object-position:center;"
      loading="eager"
    />
    <div style="position:absolute; inset:0; background:linear-gradient(to top, rgba(8,12,16,0.86) 0%, rgba(8,12,16,0.44) 55%, rgba(8,12,16,0.12) 100%);"></div>
    <div style="position:relative; max-width:820px; padding:3rem 2rem; color:#fff;">
      <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.14em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#94bfe0; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Designer Feature</p>
      <h1 style="font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem); font-weight:800; line-height:1.1; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Jordan Iverson</h1>
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:400; opacity:0.9; margin:0;">Iverson Architecture &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Modern Residential + Multifamily</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main style="max-width:860px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 1.5rem;">

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Fire as Infrastructure</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Architecture at the scale Jordan Iverson works, custom homes, urban infill, and ground-up multifamily, has different stakes than interior design. The decisions made in schematic design become load-bearing facts that the building carries for decades. When Jordan specifies a fireplace, the conversation is not about aesthetic preference. It is about how the hearth element functions within the architecture of the building: how it organizes space, how it serves multiple residents or users, and how it performs over a product lifecycle that needs to outlast three rounds of interior renovation by successive owners.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Iverson Architecture's modern residential work treats the fireplace as a spatial organizer. In an open-plan home where rooms are defined by function rather than walls, the fireplace is often the only fixed element with enough visual presence to anchor a seating zone. Jordan's multifamily work adds another layer: in a building where the fireplace serves as an amenity in a shared lounge or as a unit-differentiator in a premium floor plan, reliability and ease of maintenance become specification criteria alongside aesthetics.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        The Primo II 60 appears across Iverson Architecture's project portfolio because it satisfies both contexts simultaneously. It is a serious architectural component with the performance and installation support that a production environment demands, and it is a visually compelling element that earns its position in a residential design scheme without requiring supplemental ornament to justify it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- PULL QUOTE -->
    <section style="border-left:4px solid #1a3a5c; padding:1.25rem 1.75rem; background:#f0f4f8; margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; line-height:1.7; color:#2a2a2a; font-style:italic; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
        "In a multifamily building, the fireplace in the common lounge has to work at nine in the morning when someone is sitting with a coffee, and it has to work at nine at night when the space is full. It can't require staff to operate it and it can't fail in year two. The Primo II hits that brief. In a custom residence, the same unit gives me the see-through capability to use fire as a room separator without closing off the plan."
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:0.8125rem; color:#6b6b6b; margin:0; font-style:normal; letter-spacing:0.04em; text-transform:uppercase;">Paraphrased from Jordan Iverson's ProAdvantage program onboarding &mdash; illustrative, not a verified direct quotation</p>
    </section>

    <!-- WHY HEAT & GLO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Why Iverson Architecture Specifies Heat &amp; Glo</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        The Primo II 60 is the primary specification tool for Iverson Architecture across both residential and multifamily applications. In a single-family custom residence, the 60-inch format gives Jordan the horizontal visual weight to anchor a large-format living space without requiring a traditional masonry fireplace scale that conflicts with modern proportions. The open contemporary format reads correctly in homes where the material palette runs to polished concrete, large-format stone tile, and black steel windows: materials that have precise, hard lines and do not forgive a fireplace that sits outside their register.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        The see-through configuration of the Primo II is a specific capability that shapes Iverson Architecture's plan options in ways that other products cannot. When Jordan wants to define two zones in an open plan without cutting them off from each other, a see-through fireplace positioned on the partition axis allows fire to address both sides simultaneously. The residents on the living side see the front face. The residents on the dining or study side see the back. One mechanical installation, two room relationships. That is an architectural value that appears rarely in the gas fireplace category.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        In multifamily settings, Jordan's specification criteria expand to include installation repeatability and ongoing service access. Buildings where the same unit appears across multiple floors or in multiple common-area locations require a product that installs consistently, services predictably, and has a dealer support network that can respond to a building manager's call without a custom-parts situation. The Heat and Glo ProAdvantage program addresses those operational requirements in a way that simplifies the general contractor relationship and reduces post-occupancy friction for the property management team.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- TYPICAL PROJECT SHAPE -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">The Shape of an Iverson Architecture Project</h2>
      <h3 style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a3a5c; margin:0 0 1rem;">From Ground-Up Multifamily to Custom Infill</h3>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        A typical Iverson Architecture engagement at the multifamily scale involves a developer client building in an urban or inner-ring suburban context. The project is seeking a market position above baseline apartment product: unit finishes, common-area quality, and building identity that justify a premium and support long-term tenant retention. The fireplace in this context appears in the lobby, the resident lounge, and occasionally as a feature in larger premium unit configurations.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Jordan's residential custom projects tend to be owner-occupied primary residences on urban infill lots or suburban sites where the plan is tightly disciplined by the lot envelope. Open plans are a functional necessity as much as an aesthetic preference, and the fireplace placement is resolved in early schematic design as a spatial planning decision: where does the hearth sit in relationship to the primary circulation path, the kitchen sight line, and the primary outdoor view?
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        IntelliFire's scheduling capability is a common conversation topic in Iverson Architecture's multifamily work. A common lounge fireplace that activates on a daily schedule, at morning and evening peaks, without staff intervention or manual reset, is a building operations benefit that property managers notice and residents experience as polish. Jordan builds that conversation into the design development presentation to developer clients because it reframes the fireplace from a construction cost to an operational asset.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 1 -->
    <section style="background:#1a1a1a; color:#fff; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#94bfe0; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Trade Program</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Join ProAdvantage</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; opacity:0.8; margin:0;">Dedicated trade support, priority access, and project resources for architects and design professionals.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/pro/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Explore ProAdvantage</a>
    </section>

    <!-- INSTALLATION CARDS -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1.5rem;">Sample Installations in the Iverson Register</h2>
      <div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(240px,1fr)); gap:1.5rem;">

        <!-- Card 1 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/937081fe-73df-4957-a0ec-8c5a1bfa3a05/HNG-Primo-II_60-2_2"
              alt="Open contemporary layout with linear fireplace anchoring a large-format living space with L-shaped low seating"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Primo II 60 Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Open Contemporary Residential</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">60-inch linear fireplace wall anchoring a large open plan. L-shaped seating, stair volume, TV overhead. The modern residential specification.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 2 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/d46ab388-275f-4983-b659-7c4cd454dcf5/img-pdp-mezzo-room-"
              alt="Heat and Glo Mezzo linear gas fireplace in a contemporary living room setting"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Mezzo Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Multifamily Common Lounge</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Linear format, ribbon flame, crystal glass media. The shared amenity fireplace that holds a resident lounge from morning through evening without staff intervention.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 3 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/487a4332-ec09-4301-bb0b-d13b860a682d/HNG_Get-Inspired_Ga"
              alt="Curated collection of Heat and Glo fireplace installations in modern and contemporary settings"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Full Lineup</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Residential to Multifamily Range</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">The Heat and Glo lineup across scales and settings. Iverson Architecture draws on the full product range depending on the building type and unit mix.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 2 -->
    <section style="background:#f0f4f8; border:1px solid #bdd0e3; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#1a3a5c; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Dealer Network</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Find a Local Dealer</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Connect with a Heat and Glo dealer for architectural specification support, installation documentation, and multifamily project resources.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/where-to-buy/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Dealer Locator</a>
    </section>

    <p style="color:#888; font-size:0.875rem; border-top:1px solid #e5e0db; padding-top:1.5rem;"><a href="/architect/" style="color:#c44a08; text-decoration:none;">Back to all architects</a></p>
  </main>

</BaseLayout>
